{"query": "To mitigate the impacts of intensive arable farming, what are the effects of taking land out of production, either as set-aside or by converting it to grassland?", "summary": "Converting arable land to permanent grassland shows mixed results for wildlife. Seven individual studies examining the effects of reverting arable land to grassland found no clear benefit to wildlife, monitoring UK birds in winter and summer, wading birds in Denmark, grey partridges, brown hares in the UK, and plants in the Czech Republic (Action 561). One controlled before-and-after study from the UK showed that grey partridge numbers fell significantly following the reversion of arable fields to grassland (Actions 561, 210).

Set-aside areas show more positive effects for wildlife. Of 34 studies comparing set-aside areas with control farmed fields, 20 studies from Austria, Finland, Germany and the UK showed benefits to or higher use by all wildlife groups considered. Twelve studies found some species or groups used set-aside more than crops, others did not. Only two studies found no effect, and one found an adverse effect of set-aside (Action 156). A systematic review from the UK found significantly higher densities of farmland birds on fields removed from production and under set-aside designation than on conventionally farmed fields in both winter and summer (Action 156). Three studies looking at skylarks found mixed results for reproductive success, with two UK studies finding higher nest survival or productivity on set-aside than control fields, while one UK study found lower nest survival on set-aside (Action 156).

For butterflies and moths, restoring arable land to permanent grassland shows positive effects. Three replicated studies found that 4-5-year-old created grasslands and abandoned cropland had greater species richness of butterflies, burnet moths and all moths than conventionally managed grassland or cultivated farms. Two studies found that restored grassland had higher abundance of moths than conventional grassland or unrestored crop fields (Action 3929).", "action_ids": ["561","210","156","3929"]}

