{
  "query": "When undertaking habitat restoration on farmland, such as creating species-rich grassland, what is the typical timeframe for seeing positive ecological changes?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on 22 studies from seven European countries that included information on the length of time taken to restore grassland communities, the timeframe for seeing positive ecological changes varies significantly. Six studies saw positive signs of restoration in less than five years, while 11 studies found restoration occurred within 10 years (Action 133). Two studies found restoration took more than 10 years, and six studies found limited or slow changes in plant communities following restoration (Action 133). Two studies from Germany and the UK found differences in vegetation between restored and existing species-rich grasslands persisted even nine or 60 years after restoration (Action 133). For specific outcomes, grasslands restored from bare soil by seeding developed butterfly communities that were increasingly similar to existing high-quality grasslands over the first 10 years after establishment (Action 3929). However, over 10 years after restoration, the number of butterfly species on seeded grassland remained similar each year (Action 3929). Some studies found that grasslands created less than 10 years ago had higher species richness than grasslands created more than 20 years ago (Action 3929). Prairie restoration showed that sites restored 5-10 years ago had greater abundance of certain species than prairies restored 1-2 years ago (Action 3943).",
