{
  "query": "What are the documented effects on farmland biodiversity of switching from mineral to organic fertilizers?",
  "relevant_summary": "Seventeen studies from Austria, Belgium, Germany, Ireland, Switzerland and the UK examined the effects of using organic rather than mineral fertilizers on farmland biodiversity (Action 134). Fourteen of these studies found that areas treated with organic rather than mineral fertilizers supported higher plant diversity and cover or species richness, increased earthworm abundance or diversity, biomass and density, and increased abundance and/or species richness of some or all invertebrates investigated (Action 134). A literature review found organic fertilizers without pesticides produced highest earthworm biomass, and a trial in Belgium found more predatory beetles on an arable field two years after organic fertilizer application than on a control plot (Action 134). One study from Italy found more plants and plant biomass, but similar numbers of plant species, in plots with organic fertilizer compared to plots with inorganic fertilizer (Action 1412). However, some studies showed no effect or limited effects: one UK trial found that using organic rather than mineral fertilizers did not affect the abundance of three weed species, an Irish study found that farmyard manure had no long-term effect on invertebrates, and two UK studies found the increase in arthropod predators and springtails was only seen at a local not field scale (Action 134). Additionally, one review found that heavy applications of slurry can be toxic to common earthworms (Action 134). Studies on soil organisms showed that organic fertilizers generally resulted in more microbial biomass compared to inorganic fertilizers, though effects on other soil organisms like bacteria, nematodes, and mites were variable (Action 1366).",
