  "relevant_summary": "Based on 19 individual studies examining uncropped, cultivated margins or plots on UK farmland, several benefits and drawbacks have been observed. Benefits include increased species richness of plants, bumblebees, spiders, and ground-dwelling invertebrates and ground beetles (Action 562). These margins provide increased northern lapwing hatching success, Eurasian skylark nesting success, and establishment of rare arable plant species (Action 562). Stone curlew breeding population sizes increased, and northern lapwing, Eurasian skylark, grey partridge and yellow wagtail were found to breed in lapwing plots (Action 562). Bird nesting success was higher in fallow fields or lapwing plots than in crops (Action 213). For butterflies and moths, farms with agri-environment schemes including uncropped cultivated margins showed higher abundance of butterflies and micro-moths compared to conventional farms (Action 3923). However, several drawbacks were identified. Pernicious weeds were more commonly found on uncropped cultivated margins than conservation or conventional headlands (Action 562). The proportion of young grey partridges in the population was lower in areas with a high proportion of uncropped cultivated margins and plots (Action 562). Fewer seed-eating birds were found on fallow plots for ground-nesting birds in two out of three UK regions (Action 562). Some studies found no effect on 11 out of 12 farmland bird species or ground beetles (Action 562), and grey partridge productivity was not related to the amount of lapwing plots on a site (Action 213).",
